text: Ava remembered the heat of the forge, a constant, insistent presence from her earliest childhood.

Overly formal speech was a consistent trait; Ava spoke with precision, rarely using contractions and preferring formal phrases even in casual conversations. Phrases like “Please ensure this is completed” or “I trust this matter will be handled appropriately” were common in her dialogue.

Ava had a strict daily routine, down to the minute. Any deviation from this schedule made her anxious, and she became visibly agitated if her day didn’t go according to plan. She rose, worked, and ate at the same time every day.

She had a love of records and documentation, which extended beyond her professional life. Ava kept detailed logs of almost everything she did—whether it’s the hours she worked, the money she spent, or even notes about people she interacted with.

Social pleasantries baffled Ava; she avoided conversations she perceived as pointless, like small talk, which she saw as a waste of time. If forced into casual conversation, she often responded bluntly or not at all, shifting the subject back to practical matters.

Ava could not function without a list. Whether it’s daily tasks or long-term projects, she needed everything written out in bullet points. She often had multiple lists on hand, categorized by priority, and would cross items off with a sense of immense satisfaction.
Even in crowded areas, Ava managed to maneuver in ways that kept others at arm’s length. If someone inadvertently got too close, she stiffened, making a point to physically reposition herself.

Despite growing up in a blacksmith’s household, Ava had developed an obsession with cleanliness. She hated dirt or grime, especially on her hands or tools. Her workspace must be spotless, and she often took time to meticulously clean her surroundings before she began any task, no matter how pressing.
Ava tended to respond to emotional outbursts with cold detachment, often offering pragmatic, unemotional solutions rather than comfort.

Ava is not someone who makes friends easily or quickly. She approaches relationships cautiously, preferring to observe others from a distance before deciding if they are worth her time or emotional investment.

Ava tends to build friendships based on practicality and mutual benefit rather than emotional connections. She values efficiency, discipline, and dependability in others and is more likely to form bonds with those who share or complement these traits.

Ava has extremely high standards for those she considers close. She does not tolerate laziness, lack of discipline, or inefficiency in others, and these traits are likely to prevent potential friendships from developing.

Ava struggles with trust, particularly because she views others as unreliable until proven otherwise. Her experiences in a perfectionist household have made her self-reliant and skeptical of people’s intentions.

Ava finds emotional vulnerability uncomfortable and often avoids it altogether. While she may develop friendships that are intellectually stimulating or built on shared experiences, she is unlikely to engage in deep emotional exchanges.
Ava’s communication style can be off-putting to some. She is blunt, direct, and doesn’t sugarcoat her opinions.

Even when Ava does develop a friendship, her emotional range within that relationship will likely remain muted. She may express care or appreciation through practical acts of service or loyalty rather than open affection.
Ava does not have the patience for pretense or superficial friendships. If she finds someone annoying, untrustworthy, or lacking in the traits she values, she will not hide her displeasure for long.
For Ava, friendships are slow, practical, and built on a foundation of mutual respect and shared goals.
